WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified optical profile for the achromatic, electrically switchable
metalens developed by POSTECH and Samsung, published in Nature (April
2026). It defines the metasurface lenticular lens array, the voltage-
controlled polarisation switching between 2D and 3D modes, the achromatic
design (visible band 450–650 nm), and the performance parameters (1.2 mm
thickness, 100° viewing angle).

WHY IT EXISTS
This is the first metalens that can switch between 2D and glasses-free
3D display modes. Its achromatic design overcomes the severe chromatic
aberration that plagued earlier metalenses. GIOP integrates this profile
to support next-generation switchable 2D/3D smartphone and monitor
displays.

HOW IT WORKS
1. Metasurface Design:
   The metalens comprises TiO₂ nanofins on a glass substrate. Each
   nanofin acts as a half-wave plate, imparting a phase shift:
     φ(x,y) = (2π/λ_design) * (f - √(x² + y² + f²))
   where f is the design focal length (1.2 mm), λ_design = 530 nm.

2. Achromatic Correction:
   Multi-wavelength phase matching uses dispersion-engineered nanofin
   geometries. The phase profile is optimised for three wavelengths
   (450, 530, 630 nm) simultaneously via adjoint optimisation, achieving
   Δφ < 0.1π across the visible band.

3. Voltage-Controlled Switching:
   A liquid crystal (LC) layer above the metalens acts as a polarisation
   controller. Without voltage, the LC rotates incoming polarisation to
   match the metalens's 2D mode. With voltage applied, polarisation
   shifts to the 3D lenticular mode. Switching time < 10 ms.

4. Optical Performance:
   Thickness: 1.2 mm (metalens + LC + substrate).
   Viewing angle: 100° (horizontal), enabling multi-viewer glasses-free 3D.
   Efficiency: η > 80% (transmission at design wavelength).
   Resolution: achieves full display native resolution in 2D mode.

5. Lenticular 3D Model:
   In 3D mode, the metalens acts as a lenticular array with lens pitch
   p = 0.4 mm. Each lenslet directs light from alternating pixel columns
   to left/right eyes, creating stereoscopic parallax.
     angular_resolution = arctan(p / f) ≈ 18° per view.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Glasses-free 3D smartphones and tablets
- 3D monitors and digital signage
- GIOP spatial computing displays.

WHO USES IT
L1 Architects designing next-gen display profiles; L2 Engineers
implementing 2D/3D switching in rendering pipelines.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Enables GIOP to support switchable 2D/3D displays with a certified
metalens model, eliminating the need for glasses and overcoming the
traditional trade-off between 3D quality and viewing angle.

